```css
body {
  margin: 0; /* Remove default body margins */
}

img {
  position: fixed;
  bottom: 0;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translateX(-50%);
}
```

**Explanation:**

*   **`position: fixed;`**: This keeps the image fixed to the viewport, even when scrolling.
*   **`bottom: 0;`**:  This anchors the image to the bottom edge of the browser window.
*   **`left: 50%;`**:  Positions the left edge of the image at the horizontal center of the viewport.
*   **`transform: translateX(-50%);`**:  This shifts the image back to the left by half of its own width, effectively centering it horizontally. This is generally the best way to center elements with a known width (in this case, the image).

If the image is within a container element other than the `body`, apply these styles to the container instead.  Remember to adjust the `margin` on the container to remove any default spacing.
